{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594371"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15306"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15306"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.75,0.05,0.03,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7997"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70193"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7997"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15306"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55657"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8760"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19444"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70193"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with a history of gallstones and underwent a cholecystectomy. The histopathology examination showed thickened wall with extensive fibrosis, lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate, and deep mucosal invaginations extending into the muscular layer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute cholecystitis","Chronic cholecystitis","Choledocholithiasis","Cholesterolosis","Nonpapillary adenocarcinoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological findings are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Echronic cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features include fibrosis, chronic inflammatory infiltrate (lymphocytes and plasma cells), and Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses (mucosal invaginations). This condition commonly develops in patients with gallstones due to repeated episodes of inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E would show neutrophilic infiltration, vascular congestion or oedema in the gallbladder wall. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to stones in the common bile duct rather than a gallbladder pathology. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterolosis\u003C/strong\u003E shows accumulation of lipid-laden macrophages in the lamina propria giving a strawberry appearance. \u003Cstrong\u003ENonpapillary adenocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E would show malignant cellular features including nuclear atypia and invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic cholecystitis shows fibrosis, chronic inflammatory infiltrate, and Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses in gallbladder wall histology.","Chronic cholecystitis is commonly associated with gallstones (cholelithiasis).","Histological changes in chronic cholecystitis develop gradually due to repeated episodes of inflammation."],"references":["\u0022Chronic recurrent cholecystitis, HE 2\u0022 by Path  is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Histopathology_of_chronic_cholecystitis#/media/File:Chronic_recurrent_cholecystitis,_HE_2.JPG","Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Lammert F, Gurusamy K, Ko CW, Miquel JF, M\u00e9ndez-S\u00e1nchez N, Portincasa P, van Erpecum KJ, van Laarhoven CJ, Wang DQ. Gallstones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Apr 28;2:16024. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.24. PMID: 27121416"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55657"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15306"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21153"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21153"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YpUk9kfCxupWOSwVoGqO7REYg2E7Ig.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/YpUk9kfCxupWOSwVoGqO7REYg2E7Ig.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1000}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55657"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T07:53:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T14:55:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7997"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70193"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"descript